<br>
In my limited experience, when our warder is gone, we're soon to follow. While others have strong offense or strong defense, we're rather weak in both departments. A beastlord in a duel is all about the opponent's indecision, and our best bet is to keep him from committing to either us or our pet.<br>
<br>
If he goes after the pet, Flash of Light him. Again, and again, and again. Easily resisted, but the mana cost is ~0, and it WILL land. Many folks just freeze when that monitor goes dark, and that's the time to get in there and do a bit of damage yourself.<br>
<br>
If he goes straight for you, it's time to kite. A clicky snare is wonderful here, of course, but not often an option for me, so I just run like a little girl, and pull out a 2HB to occasionally stop and joust, warder chewing his backside the whole while. That seems to get old after a while, so they go back to the pet. Repeat Step 1.<br>
<br>
There's some other tricks to help out. Shrinking oneself (especially while the opponent's blinded) will give you long seconds of freedom while they try to find you, and when they do, it's easier to avoid them or get behind them. Our DoTs and nukes are pretty pathetic, but they work, and a decent way to counter Damage Shields. But our best bet is still to encourage the other to take both of us on in stages. At 46, with my wee little 31 warder still, between us we have over 3600 hit points. That's a lot for a level-appropriate opponent to chew through.<br>
<br>
All very subjective, as any discussion like this is bound to be, and yes, I've left out countless 'what ifs', so take what I've said as suggestions, not pwnzerage. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
